long_desc.thetext: Retargetting to M2, as I don't expect to finish work on these before this week's build(s)

Hi Hendy, I got the code from the github repository and switched to the stackoverflow-traverse branch. I think the code which you are trying to compiler is from JavaMapReduce.java. The code has dependencies on gridgain and FluentIterable packages.
Will it be possible for you to give us a example which is not dependent on these packages?
I will continue working with the example mentioned in Comment 2.
Thanks

(In reply to Hendy Irawan from comment #4) > Hi Shankha, > > Here's a much simpler example based on Comment 2 (but slightly different).
On HEAD I don't see any problems with this sample code.

Problem reproducible with example mentioned in Comment 2.
We seem to corrupt the stack and thus elements lying on the stack while error recovery in Parser.parse().
Since the data structures are corrupted we read incorrect values and thus get into a cycle which causes the stack overflow.
Thanks

(In reply to shankha banerjee from comment #6) > Problem reproducible with example mentioned in Comment 2. > > We seem to corrupt the stack and thus elements lying on the stack while > error recovery in Parser.parse(). > > Since the data structures are corrupted we read incorrect values and thus > get into a cycle which causes the stack overflow.
Fix and test here: http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/?id=8ddb795897861fe94c9269feaf63d0b53ecdb996.
The earlier parse tree had unwarranted cycles - the present recovered parse tree isn't quite perfect, but it has harmless redundant elements instead of cycles.
Once we have a owner for code assist, this can be revisited.
Verified for Mars 4.5M2 using I20140915-2000 build.
Jay this is a must for 4.4.2 along with https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=446765
